In the formulation of [[convenience food|food products]], the '''bliss point''' is the amount of an ingredient such as [[salt]], [[sugar]], or [[fat]] which optimizes [[tastiness]]. Pioneering work on the bliss point was carried out by American [[market research]]er and [[Psychophysics|psychophysicist]] [[Howard Moskowitz]], known for his successful work in product creation and optimization for foods ranging from spaghetti sauce to [[soft drink]]s.<ref name=NYTMag022013>{{cite news|title=The Extraordinary Science of Addictive Junk Food|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/24/magazine/the-extraordinary-science-of-junk-food.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=March 1, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times Magazine|date=February 20, 2013|author=Michael Moss}}</ref> Moskowitz describes the bliss point as "that sensory profile where you like food the most.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wildt|first1=Grace|title=The Bliss Point|url=http://www.retroreport.org/voices/the-bliss-point/|website=Retro Report|publisher=Retro Report|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>
The bliss point for salt, sugar, or fat is a range within which perception is that there is neither too much nor too little, but the "just right" amount of saltiness, sweetness, or richness. The human body has evolved to favor foods delivering these tastes: the brain responds with a "reward" in the form of a jolt of [[endorphin]]s, remembers what we did to get that reward, and makes us want to do it again, an effect run by [[dopamine]], the [[neurotransmitter]]. Combinations of sugar, fat, and salt act [[synergistic]]ally, and are more rewarding than any one alone. In food product optimization, the goal is to include two or three of these nutrients at their bliss point.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://courses.bio.indiana.edu/L104-Bonner/F12/imagesF12/L8/BlissPoint.html | title=Biology of Food: The Bliss Point | publisher=Indiana University (Department of Biology) | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fcourses.bio.indiana.edu%2FL104-Bonner%2FF12%2FimagesF12%2FL8%2FBlissPoint.html&date=2015-04-03 | archive-date=4 March 2015 |accessdate=2 April 2015}} From Biology of Food, Dept. of Biology, Indiana University.</ref>
