{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st-century philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Jason Martin Wirth''' |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1963|2|3}} |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy|Continental]] | institutions = [[Seattle University]] |main_interests = [[moral philosophy]], [[post-Kantian philosophy]] | thesis_title = The Conspiracy of Being: FWJ von Schelling and Conscientiousness before the Freedom of Philosophy | thesis_url = | thesis_year = May 1994 | doctoral_advisor = [[Dennis J. Schmidt]] | doctoral_students = |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = [[State University of New York at Binghamton]] (Ph.D.) | alma_mater = |influences = [[Kant]], [[Heidegger]] |influenced = |awards = The Torch Bearer Award, John Tich Award |website = }}
'''Jason Martin Wirth''' is an American philosopher and professor of philosophy at [[Seattle University]]. He was the [[Theiline Pigott McCone Chair in Humanities]] from 2014 to 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Theiline Pigott McCone Chair in Humanities - Endowments and Partnerships - Office of the Dean - College of Arts and Sciences |url=https://www.seattleu.edu/artsci/office-of-the-dean/endowments-and-partnerships/pigott-mccone/ |website=[[Seattle University]] |accessdate=30 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref> He won The Torch Bearer Award in 2018. Wirth is known for his research on [[environmental philosophy]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hayes |first1=Josh |title=Jason M. Wirth, Mountains, Rivers, and the Great Earth: Reading Gary Snyder and Dōgen in an Age of Ecological Crisis |journal=Frontiers of Philosophy in China]] |date=11 January 2017 |volume=12 |issue=4 |pages=666–671 |doi=10.3868/s030-006-017-0045-4 |url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.3868/s030-006-017-0045-4 |accessdate=30 September 2018 |language=en |issn=1673-355X}}</ref>
==Books== * ''Mountains, Rivers, and the Great Earth: Reading Gary Snyder and Dōgen in an Age of Ecological Crisis'', SUNY 2017 * ''Commiserating with Devastated Things'', Fordham 2015 * ''Schelling’s Practice of the Wild'', SUNY 2015 * ''The Conspiracy of Life: Meditations on Schelling and His Time'', SUNY 2003 * ''Nietzsche and Other Buddhas'', Indiana, spring 2019
