{{Infobox person | name = Leslee Udwin | image = P1140027 (17223616286).jpg | caption = [[Norah O'Donnell]], Leslee Udwin and [[Barkha Dutt]] | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Savyon]], [[Israel]]<ref name="Granta Interview">{{cite journal | url=https://granta.com/interview-leslee-udwin/ | title=Interview: Leslee Udwin | author=Faleiro, Sonia| authorlink = Sonia Faleiro | journal=[[Granta Magazine]] | date=April 2, 2015 | issue=130}}</ref> | spouse = Kim Romer (born 1959) | children = 2 | years_active = | occupation = Filmmaker, Human Rights Activist | website = | awards = [[BAFTA]], [[Peabody Award|Peabody]], [[Amnesty International Media Award]], [[Royal Television Society Award]] }}
'''Leslee Udwin''' (born 1957)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://companycheck.co.uk/director/903104839 |title=Leslee Udwin |date= |website=Company Check |publisher= |access-date=}}</ref> is a British filmmaker,<ref>{{cite news|title=Nirbhaya Documentary, Banned in India, Premieres in US; Meryl Streep, Frieda Pinto Attend|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/nirbhaya-documentary-banned-in-india-premieres-in-us-meryl-streep-friedo-pinto-attend-745456|accessdate=10 March 2015|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]|date=March 10, 2015}}</ref> actress, director, producer and human rights activist.
==Early life== She was born in [[Savyon]], [[Israel]], to a European Jewish family with roots in England, Germany and Lithuania. At the age of about nine she went with her family to South Africa where they spent the next ten years. Her parents were [[religious Jews]], but at the age of about thirteen, she rebelled against Judaism, particularly the morning prayer called [[Shacharit]], in which men say, "I thank God that he did not make me a woman".<ref name="Granta Interview"/><ref name="staticmass">{{cite web|title=Exclusive Interview With Leslee Udwin - West Is West (Movie, 2010) Exclusive | work=Static Mass Emporium|url=http://staticmass.net/exclusive-interviews/exclusive-interview-with-leslee-udwin/|author=Samuel, Patrick|accessdate=October 10, 2017|date=February 22, 2011}}</ref>
==Career==
While her father wanted her to be a lawyer, Udwin supported herself working in theatre and teaching while at university; in her first year she was raped, a fact she told nobody about at the time.<ref name="Granta Interview"/> She began her career as an actress at the [[Space Theatre in Cape Town]], one of the only two integrated (‘multi-cultural’) theatres in South Africa, playing in the ''[[Duchess of Malfi]]'' and [[Stephen Poliakoff]]’s ''[[Hitting Town]]''. Not wishing to work in ‘[[White South African|whites-only]]’ theatres, her work possibilities in South Africa were limited, so she moved to London<ref name="Sassy HK">{{cite web | url=https://www.sassyhongkong.com/influencers-sassy-supports-leslee-udwin-indias-daughter/ | title=Sassy Supports: Leslee Udwin, producer of documentary 'India's Daughter' | publisher=Sassy Hong Kong | date=April 26, 2016 | accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> at age twenty-one.<ref name="Granta Interview"/> There she acted in plays at the [[Royal Court Theatre|Royal Court]], [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] and [[Cheek By Jowl]] playing roles like [[Lady Macbeth]], Isobel in ''[[The Mayor of Zalamea]]'', Masha in [[Chekhov]]'s ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]'', Nora in ''[[A Doll's House]]'', etc. On screen she appeared in the [[BBC Shakespeare Series]] production of ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]'' (1980).<ref name="Sassy HK"/> In 1989 she set a legal precedent in the [[High Court of England]] against a criminal landlord [[Nicholas van Hoogstraten]] who harassed her and her fellow tenants in their rent act protected apartment block in West London. She then turned her real life two and a half year battle against Hoogstraten and its victorious outcome into a drama documentary ''[[Sitting Targets]]'' (1989) for the BBC drama series ''[[Screen Two#Series Five|Screen Two]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/617559863ea54894886591c18791e3aa | title=Screen Two: Sitting Targets - BBC Two England | publisher=[[BBC Genome]] | work=[[Radio Times]] | date=March 19, 1989 | accessdate=October 9, 2017}}</ref><ref name="BC Spotlight">{{cite web | url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/comment/spotlight/2011/leslee-udwin | title=Leslee Udwin interview | publisher=[[British Council]] Film | work=Spotlight | date=2011 | accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> feeling that this optimistic story should inspire as many people as possible; this was her first experience behind the camera.<ref name="Forbes"/>
After ten years as an actress<ref name="Granta Interview"/> she wanted more: "It was an exciting career, but working as an actress was not enough for me – I began to want to choose and not just interpret the stories being told." This led her to become a producer.<ref name="Sassy HK"/><ref name="BC Spotlight"/> She started her production company, '''Assassin Films''', in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.linkedin.com/pub/leslee-udwin/55/454/330|title=Leslee Udwin Profile|author=|date=|website=[[Linkedin]]|publisher=|access-date=October 10, 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150309153531/https://uk.linkedin.com/pub/leslee-udwin/55/454/330|archivedate=March 9, 2015|df=}}</ref> Her well-known productions include the films ''[[East Is East (1999 film)|East is East]]'' (1999), ''[[Mrs Ratcliffe's Revolution]]'' (2007), and ''[[West Is West (2010 film)|West is West]]'' (2010), and the documentary ''[[India's Daughter]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0879889/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm | title=Leslee Udwin Biography | publisher=[[IMDb]] | accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/mar/04/indias-daughter-director-appeals-to-narendra-modi-over-broadcast-ban | title=Delhi rape documentary-maker appeals to Narendra Modi over broadcast ban | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=4 March 2015 | accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.film4.com/special-features/interviews/careers-leslee-udwin | title=Careers in Film: East Is East producer Leslee Udwin | publisher=film4.com | accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="Forbes">{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/deniserestauri/2017/06/05/women-take-action-how-one-unbelievable-event-launched-a-powerful-career/#88cec9e6f272 | title=Women Take Action: How One Unbelievable Event Launched A Powerful Career | work=[[Forbes]] | date=June 5, 2017 | accessdate=October 10, 2017 | author=Restauri, Denise}}</ref>
Leslee is no stranger to successful campaigning films. ''[[Who Bombed Birmingham?]]'' (1990, starring [[John Hurt]]) for [[HBO]] and [[Granada TV]], directly led to the release of the ‘[[Birmingham Six]]’ after 17 years of wrongful imprisonment. The morning after the broadcast [[Margaret Thatcher]] stood up in the House of Commons, seething with rage shouting, "We will not have trial by television in this country."<ref name="Granta Interview"/> Her feature film ''East is East'' (35 prestigious awards worldwide, including British Oscar for Best Film) did much to promote tolerance and the celebration of diversity as between the Asian and British communities and has become a classic film taught in schools across Europe. Her documentary ''India's Daughter'', has been critically acclaimed around the globe, won 32 awards (including the [[Peabody Award]] and the [[Amnesty International Media Award]] for Best Documentary 2016) and sparked a global movement to end [[violence against women]] and girls.
The searing insights yielded by the 2½ year journey making ''India’s Daughter'', led Leslee to found UK-and-US-based Not for Profit global education initiative '''ThinkEqual''', of which she is the CEO.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thinkequal.com/ | title=ThinkEqual | publisher=ThinkEqual | accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> Leslee was voted by the ''[[NY Times]]'' the No 2 Most Impactful Woman of 2015 (second to [[Hillary Clinton]]), and has been awarded the prestigious Swedish [[Anna Lindh Human Rights Prize]] (previously won by [[Madeleine Albright]]) in 2015.<ref name="Anna Lindh Memorial Prize">{{cite web | url=http://www.government.se/articles/2015/09/ministers-received-filmmaker-leslee-udwin/ | title=Ministers received filmmaker Leslee Udwin | publisher=Government.se | date=September 11, 2015 | accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Forbes"/> She has also been named Safe’s Global Hero of 2015, and a Global Thinker by ''[[Foreign Policy]]''.
==Personal life== She lives in London, UK when not on assignments in places such as Copenhagen and India.<ref name="Granta Interview"/>
== Controversies == ''India's Daughter'' was banned by the Indian government who were alerted to its 'undesirable nature' by a number of [[Indian feminists]] including [[Indira Jaisingh]], [[Urvashi Bhutalia]],<ref name="TNS">{{cite web | url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/feminism-grew-out-of-history-in-india-urvashi-butalia/#.Wdxb4nWGP0o | title="Feminism grew out of our history in India" — Urvashi Butalia | work=TNS - The News on Sunday | date=May 24, 2015 | accessdate=October 10, 2017 | author=Akhtar, Aasim| authorlink = Aasim Akhtar}}</ref> Vrinder Grover, [[Kavita Krishnan]],<ref name="Granta Interview"/> Dr [[Devaki Jain]]. The BJP government accused Udwin of "a conspiracy to shame India" and wish to "decimate its tourist industry". Udwin listed statistics at the end of the documentary to draw attention to the fact that violence against women and girls is a global pandemic to which no country is immune. She has said she believes the reason for the ban is "India's current obsession with nationalism and image which makes it reluctant to look in the mirror".
