'''''Werner's Nomenclature of Colours''''' is a book of named [[colour sample]]s compiled by [[Abraham Gottlob Werner]], and subsequently amended by [[Patrick Syme]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisiscolossal.com/2018/01/werners-nomenclature-of-colours/|title=Werner's Nomenclature of Colours: a Pre-Photographic Guide for Artists and Naturalists|last=Kate|first=Sierzputowski|date=2018-01-31|work=Colossal|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref> The book, first published in 1814, was used by [[Charles Darwin]] in his scientific observations.<ref name="architecturaldigest">{{Cite news|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/pantone-there-was-werners-nomenclature-of-colours|title=Before Pantone There Was Werner’s Nomenclature of Colours {{!}} Architectural Digest|last=St Clair|first=Kassia|date=February 5, 2018|work=Architectural Digest|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/the-book-that-colored-charles-darwins-world|title=The Book That Colored Charles Darwin’s World|last=Nijhuis|first=Michelle|date=January 27, 2018|work=The New Yorker|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref> Werner's ''Nomenclature'' can be viewed as a predecessor of modern named colour systems such as [[Pantone]].<ref name=architecturaldigest/>

